<br><IMG SRC="http://www.gregwesson.com/power.jpg"></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=setch>Setch</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Channeler</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(8/19/02 4:22:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=19723.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Hayburner or shoe leather?</span><hr size=1> eh. I think some folks here have the wrong idea.<br>
<br>
If you buy the horse, it will help you quadding.<br>
<br>
Not for speed, but for mana.<br>
<br>
Think about it this way: pillar spells take about 5 seconds to cast. And you're standing still a little longer than that, when you account for human error. Chances are, if you're on horseback you're going to catch a med tic during that cast. Which is worth 20 mana or more.<br>
<br>
Accounting for specialization and a focus ring, Pillar of lightning (for example) only costs 292 mana. If you're getting back 20 mana each time you cast it, that's a ~8% efficiency boost.<br>
<br>
And that's not counting the random med tics you catch when you are stopped for other reasons (looting, stopping to check your progress, whatever).<br>
<br>
Now, I can't tell you whether these benefits make the horse worth the cost. That's a question of how rich you are or how lucky. I got my own horse through an uber friend who was quitting the game and decided to spend some cash on her pals. Lose a friend, gain a horse... lucky? I dunno...<br>
<br>
Anyway,  I doubt I would have bought one on my own at this point. But, having it, I use it all the time, and I believe it helps (although, there a lot of things in luclin that help quadding; KEI, focuses, horses, AAxp; and it's not easy to figure out the relative value of each)<br>
<br>
Point of closure; if you buy a horse to quad on get the cheapest one. The accel thing sucks, and you will need to turn your horse graphics off to get rid of it. Which means you'll get no movement benefits from the horse... so how fast it runs isn't very important for quadding. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/unatile.showPublicProfile?language=EN>natile</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(8/19/02 5:18:46 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=19723.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Hayburner or shoe leather?</span><hr size=1> Setch is correct. I love fighting solo in dungeons for the challenge, and if it wasn't for my horse I would never quad. The invis bug is annoying, but it has helped ensure me that the horse makes a difference. When I quad toilers in ME, I click off the horse and invis when I med. When I forget to recast the horse I will end my quads with about 8-15% less mana than if I had cast the horse. You get mana while snaring, while nuking, while waiting 28 seconds for your stupid velious robe to cast on a runner... and the best one, if you make a mistake like I do all the time and your quad kite turns into a 20 kite, you can med while you kite without having to sit and stand to save your life.<br>
